Here's your migrated code and the key pitfalls to watch for.

## Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` + `Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` in Stop | Blocking wait | `Thread.Join(timeout)` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work â€” same logic that was in the ThreadAbortException block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. Loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't exit in time â€” log a warning.
                // There is NO equivalent to Abort() in modern .NET.
                // If the thread is stuck, the process must be designed
                // so that GetNextItem/ProcessItem actually check the token.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token.** If it blocks on a queue or I/O without checking the token, `Cancel()` won't wake it up and `Stop()` will hang:

```csharp
// âťŚ Before â€” blocks forever, ignores cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// âś… After â€” wakes up immediately on cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
```

**2. `Thread.Sleep` â†’ `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne`.** If `ProcessItem` has any `Thread.Sleep` calls, replace them â€” `Sleep` ignores the token:

```csharp
// âťŚ Won't wake on cancellation
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// âś… Returns immediately when token is cancelled
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

**3. Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` â€” leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The `IDisposable` implementation on the class handles this.

**4. Cancellation is not immediate.** Unlike `Thread.Abort` which injected an exception at any point, cooperative cancellation only fires at the *next checkpoint* (`token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`, a token-aware API call, or the loop condition check). If `ProcessItem` does long CPU work, add checkpoints inside it:

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var record in item.Records)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Transform(record);
    }
}
```

**5. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` silently.** The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from a bug. Without the filter, you could mask real errors.
